Route Purpose <code>POST /jobs</code> Submit a run. Body <code>{"input": {&lt;chat fields&gt;}, "session_id": &lt;optional&gt;, "construct": &lt;optional&gt;}</code>. Returns <code>202 {job_id, status}</code>. <code>GET /jobs</code> List jobs, newest first. Filter with <code>?status=</code> and <code>?session_id=</code>. <code>GET /jobs/{id}</code> Job status and, when terminal, its result. <code>GET /jobs/{id}/updates?since=&lt;seq&gt;</code> The update log past a sequence cursor. <code>GET /jobs/{id}/stream</code> SSE stream of updates: replay from cursor, then live tail. <code>POST /jobs/{id}/cancel</code> Cancel a queued or running job. <p>The <code>input</code> object is your agent's normal chat request body. Pass a <code>session_id</code> (from <code>POST /sessions</code>) to run the job against an existing session; omit it for a one-off run.</p> <p>For a one-off run, add a <code>construct</code> object — the same construction data as <code>POST /sessions</code> (state and any nested linked agents) — to build a fresh agent for the job. Its dependencies are injected server-side, just like for sessions. Session-bound jobs reuse the session's existing agent and ignore <code>construct</code>.</p> <pre><code># One-off job that builds its own agent from a construct payload
httpx.post("http://localhost:8000/jobs", json={
    "input": {"user_input": "Summarize the latest results"},
    "construct": {"topic": {"name": "kv-cache"}},
})
</code></pre>
